         <abstract>
            <p>Let p and q be primes such that &lt;tex-math&gt;$p \equiv 1 (\operatorname{mod} q)$&lt;/tex-math&gt;. Let a be an integer such that &lt;tex-math&gt;$a^{(p-1)}/q} \equiv 1 (\operatorname{mod} p)$&lt;/tex-math&gt;. In 1972, H. C. Williams gave an algorithm which determines a solution of the congruence &lt;tex-math&gt;$x^q \equiv a (\operatorname{mod} p)$&lt;/tex-math&gt; in O(q&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; log p) steps, once an integer b has been found such that &lt;tex-math&gt;$(b^q - a)^{(p-1)/q} \not\equiv 0, 1 (\operatorname{mod} p)$&lt;/tex-math&gt;. A step is an arithmetic operation (mod p) or an arithmetic operation on q-bit integers. We present a refinement of this algorithm which determines a solution in O(q&lt;sup&gt;4&lt;/sup&gt;) + O(q&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; log p) steps, once b has been determined. Thus the new algorithm is better when q is small compared with p.</p>
          </abstract>
